@rural_stakeholders
title: Rural Community Stakeholders
subtitle: Getting Everyone to the Table
new-page: true

Narration: Rural communities have their own unique dynamics. For holistic management to work, you'll want to involve representatives from all the key groups that make up your community.

Narration: A farming drone flies overhead, apparently trying to plant seeds in the clouds. Innovation meets confusion.

Narration: Consider involving: farmers and landowners, local business owners, parents and families, youth representatives, elderly community members, local government officials, environmental stewards, and cultural/religious leaders.

- @rural_comprehensive: Include all key rural stakeholder groups
- @rural_limited: Focus on just the main decision-makers

@rural_comprehensive
on-arrival: rural_stakeholders = "comprehensive"
go-to: stakeholder_commitment

@rural_limited
on-arrival: rural_stakeholders = "limited"
go-to: stakeholder_warning

@urban_stakeholders
title: Urban Community Stakeholders
subtitle: Representing City Diversity
new-page: true

Narration: Urban communities are incredibly diverse. Getting holistic management right means hearing from all the different voices that make up your neighborhood or district.

Narration: A street cleaning robot passes by, apparently convinced that graffiti is a form of advanced urban agriculture. It's been watering the walls for weeks.

Narration: Consider involving: residents from different backgrounds, local business owners, youth and student representatives, parents and families, elderly residents, community organization leaders, local government representatives, and advocates for different interest groups.

- @urban_comprehensive: Include diverse urban stakeholder groups
- @urban_limited: Focus on established community leaders

@urban_comprehensive
on-arrival: urban_stakeholders = "comprehensive"
go-to: stakeholder_commitment

@urban_limited
on-arrival: urban_stakeholders = "limited"
go-to: stakeholder_warning

@mixed_stakeholders
title: Mixed Community Stakeholders
subtitle: Bridging Different Worlds
new-page: true

Narration: Mixed communities often bridge rural and urban elements, creating unique opportunities and challenges. Your stakeholder group should reflect this diversity.

Narration: A delivery drone hovers uncertainly between a farm stand and a coffee shop, apparently unable to decide which represents the "real" community. Both, obviously.

Narration: Consider involving: residents from different areas (rural and urban parts), local farmers and business owners, commuters and long-time residents, parents and youth from different backgrounds, community organization leaders, and representatives of different economic interests.

- @mixed_comprehensive: Include stakeholders from all community segments
- @mixed_limited: Focus on the most vocal community members

